   15148             : /*
   15149             : The routines lists in file and namespace scopes is normally constructed by
   15150             : appending newly created routine entries at the end of the appropriate list.
   15151             : The one exception occurs when a previously declared routine is defined: In
   15152             : that case we must move the original entry to the end of the list.  Since the
   15153             : routines list is singly-linked, traversing the list each time we encounter a
   15154             : definition can be prohibitively expensive with the following not-so-rare
   15155             : scenario.  Suppose the sequence of routine declarations in a translation unit
   15156             : is as follows:
   15157             :         <declaration of routine #1>
   15158             :         <declaration of routine #2>
   15159             :         ...
   15160             :         <declaration of routine #N>   N large
   15161             :         <declaration (without definition) of routine F>
   15162             :         <declaration (without definition) of routine G>
   15163             :         ...
   15164             :         <definition of routine F>
   15165             :         <definition of routine G>
   15166             :         ...
   15167             : (The large number of initial routine declarations is a common consequence
   15168             : of including library header files.)  Each definition of F, G, ... requires
   15169             : that the entry corresponding to the prior declaration of F, G, ... be found,
   15170             : which in turn requires a traversal of a large portion of the list of routines.
   15171             : If we find and move prior declarations one at a time, we end up performing an
   15172             : expensive traversal for every definition, and the total cost of these
   15173             : traversals can become a very significant fraction of total compilation time.
   15174             : 
   15175             : Instead, we attempt to amortize the cost of traversing the routines list by
   15176             : scheduling moves in an array of "move descriptions".  At an appropriate time
   15177             : (e.g., when a scope is popped), these "moves" are then sorted to enhance the
   15178             : likeliness that a simultaneous traversal of the routines list and the array
   15179             : of move descriptions will allow most or all scheduled moves to be performed.
   15180             : */
   15181             : 
   15182             : typedef struct a_routine_move_descr {
   15183             :   a_routine_ptr
   15184             :                 routine;
   15185             :                         /* A pointer to a routine that must be moved. */
   15186             :   a_routine_ptr
   15187             :                 insert_after;
   15188             :                         /* A pointer to a placeholder routine entry after
   15189             :                            which the routine should be inserted.  (Placeholder
   15190             :                            routines are never themselves moved.) */
   15191             :   a_seq_number
   15192             :                 first_pos;
   15193             :                         /* The sequence number of the first declaration of the
   15194             :                            routine to move.  This position participates in the
   15195             :                            sorting of the "move descriptions" and must be
   15196             :                            recorded when the move is scheduled because the
